                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d41">
                <head>41. National Security Action Memorandum No. 75<note n="0" type="source"
                        xml:id="d41fn0">Source: Department of State, <gloss target="#t_SS1"
                            >S/S</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 72 D 316,
                        NSAM 75. Confidential. A copy was sent to the Director, <gloss
                            target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-08-20">August 20, 1961</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Polish Government Taxes on Relief Packages</item>
                </list>
                <p>Is there anything we can properly do to persuade the Polish Government to lift
                    their present restrictions in taxes which Polish recipients of a relief package
                    must pay. I understand that shipment of used clothing makes up the bulk of the
                        traffic.<note n="1" xml:id="d41fn1">In a memorandum to the President,
                        October 19, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> reported
                        that Polish customs levies had been reduced and that discussions with
                        approximately 150 recipients of these packages produced only three
                        complaints, all related to duties on new clothing imports. “The Embassy
                        expressed its continuing belief that the new tariff presents no difficulty
                        to recipients of normal gift parcels.” (Ibid.)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">John F. Kennedy</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d41fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
